all the heavy planet detail belongs in a descend/focus mode, not in the system view. At 12–58px on screen, the only thing that matters is silhouette, colour, orbit and a couple of readable status markers; the 6-layer shader stack should be reserved for one selected hero planet at a time.

Why your critique is spot on
At the current camera/FOV, planets are small enough that shoreline foam, cloud shadows and city lights are literally below the “visible detail” threshold, but every layer would still cost a full draw call and shader pass per planet.

Procedural planet demos and astronomy shaders show that realistic atmospheres, rings, clouds and terrain use multiple textures and uniforms per object; replicating that across dozens of worlds is expensive and overkill for tiny dots.

Hero-style planet shaders (Earth, Saturn, custom alien worlds) are designed for close-up viewing, not icon-size system maps, which matches exactly what you’re arguing for.

So yeah: keep the current simple, legible “what to work on” system at 60fps, and hang the spectacle off a single zoomed-in planet at a time.

Recommended architecture: two modes, one hero
1. System view (what you already have)
Keep this close to how it is now:

Instanced basic meshes (spheres/icosahedrons) with cheap materials: solid albedo, simple emissive, maybe one noise-based rim.

Per-repo differentiation via:

radius (size),

orbit radius/angle,

colour “family”,

basic state icons (e.g. a small overlay for “has PRs”, “has quests”).

Interaction: hover to preview, click to “select world and descend”.

No multi-layer shaders, no render-to-texture, no volumetric effects here. It stays as your fast “universe map UI”.

2. Focus view / descend mode (one world)
This is the hero planet scene that you show when a repo is selected:

Camera transitions:

System → orbit of world → close planet view in one smooth move (Three.js camera tween / R3F spring).

Only one planet uses the full shader stack:

higher-res mesh,

terrain/ocean/cloud/atmosphere overlays,

rings, moons, lights.

All other planets either:

disappear,

or render as ultra-cheap blurred dots/background constellations.

This matches your core product idea: choosing one world to descend into is choosing one world to focus on. The “wow” becomes the reward for hyperfocus, which fits the HyperFocus z0ne thesis perfectly.

Hero planet shader: lean but lush
You still get your full cinematic planet, just for one repo at a time:

Base mesh: ico-sphere or subdivided sphere with vertex-displacement noise for terrain.

Day/night textures or procedural colours: use a day colour ramp and a night emissive map (or procedural sampling) like the classic Earth shader examples.

Ocean: mask by height (sea level) with depth-based colour gradient and a thin shoreline glow band; cheap to implement with a couple of uniforms.

Clouds: second sphere slightly larger than the surface, with scrolling noise; can be one extra material, not full volumetric.

Atmosphere rim: simple Fresnel term (dot of normal and view) for edge glow, inspired by Earth/Saturn shaders.

Moons/rings: separate meshes driven by your PRs→moons mapping and any other signals you keep.

This is exactly how people build realistic planets in Three.js/WebGL today: one hero globe with multiple textures/uniforms, cloud shells and atmospherics, all focused on a single object in view.

